INTRODUCTION

Welcome to the R data.table tutorial! Data.table is the fastest way in R to handle large tables (data.frames) in a database-like manner. Several online tutorials are available for more explanations (see below), and a good introduction can be displayed by typing data.table in the RStudio Help tab. This document summarizes the most useful approaches to using data.table.

First we load data.table package and an example of lab data from the ./Data/ folder:

library(data.table)
(load('./Data/labs.rda')) # the parenthesis makes the code print the result of the command, in this case "labs", the loaded object
## [1] "labs"

The classes of the loaded object “labs” are:

class(labs)
## [1] "data.table" "data.frame"

This is because data.table is an extension of the data.frame class, inheriting all its properties plus additional ones. Contrary to data.frames, printing the data.table by typing its name on th console will show the first and last 5 rows:

labs # similar to rbind(head(as.data.frame(labs),5),tail(as.data.frame(labs),5))

Subsetting data.tables

In general, data.tables can be assessed like data.frames:

  1. Any column of the data.frame can be displayed with the data.table name followed by the $ and the column name
head(labs$Test)
## [1] "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP"
  1. The data.table name followed by [i, j] where i represents rows and j represents columns:
labs[1:6,c('Test','RESULT')]
##    Test RESULT
## 1: AGAP     -9
## 2: AGAP     -7
## 3: AGAP     -4
## 4: AGAP     -1
## 5: AGAP     -1
## 6: AGAP      1
labs[1:6,2:3]
##    Test RESULT
## 1: AGAP     -9
## 2: AGAP     -7
## 3: AGAP     -4
## 4: AGAP     -1
## 5: AGAP     -1
## 6: AGAP      1

However, many more functionalities are available for subsetting rows and columns and perform other operations.

Note that to get the same result as a default data.frame subsetting (i.e drop=TRUE), you have to use column names without quotes. If you use the quotes, it returns a data.table with one column:

labs[1:6,Test] # same as as.data.frame(labs)[1:6,'Test'] or as.data.frame(labs)[1:6,'Test',drop=TRUE]
## [1] "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP"
labs[1:6,'Test'] # same as as.data.frame(labs)[1:6,'Test',drop=FALSE]
##    Test
## 1: AGAP
## 2: AGAP
## 3: AGAP
## 4: AGAP
## 5: AGAP
## 6: AGAP

The reason omitting the quotes works for column names is that in data.table, all the column names are attached to the data.table environment, i.e. they become objects (variables) that are accessed inside the […] of a data.table. This is very useful because if you don’t remember the column name you can press the tab key inside the […] in RStudio and it will show candidate column names. Try typing labs[1:6 followed by a comma and the TAB in the RStudio console. After pressing the TAB key, try typing hi or no.

The function .(…) allows subsetting by multiple columns:

labs[1:6,.(Test,RESULT)] 
##    Test RESULT
## 1: AGAP     -9
## 2: AGAP     -7
## 3: AGAP     -4
## 4: AGAP     -1
## 5: AGAP     -1
## 6: AGAP      1

This is equivalent to labs[1:6,c(‘Test’,‘RESULT’)] and labs[1:6,list(Test,RESULT)] but not labs[1:6,list(‘Test’,‘RESULT’)]

labs[1:6,list('Test','RESULT')] 
##      V1     V2
## 1: Test RESULT

Various ways of subsetting in j (columns)

labs[1:2,Test] # returned as a vector
## [1] "AGAP" "AGAP"
labs[1:2,.(Test)] # returned as a one column data.table
##    Test
## 1: AGAP
## 2: AGAP
labs[1:2,"Test"] # returned as a one column data.table
##    Test
## 1: AGAP
## 2: AGAP
labs[1:2,.(Test,RESULT)] # returned as two column data.table
##    Test RESULT
## 1: AGAP     -9
## 2: AGAP     -7
labs[1:2,c("Test","RESULT")] # same as above
##    Test RESULT
## 1: AGAP     -9
## 2: AGAP     -7
labs[1:2,.("Test","RESULT")] # NOT the desired result
##      V1     V2
## 1: Test RESULT
labs[1:2,.(Test,RESULT)][[2]] # second column returned as a vector
## [1] -9 -7
cols <- c("Test","RESULT")
labs[1:2,..cols] # if you want to use a variable containing column names, use ..variable in j
##    Test RESULT
## 1: AGAP     -9
## 2: AGAP     -7
labs[1:2,cols,with=FALSE] # the with = FALSE argument means j is NOT interpreted as a column name
##    Test RESULT
## 1: AGAP     -9
## 2: AGAP     -7
try(labs[1:2,cols]) # gives an error because cols is not found in column names (default with = TRUE)
labs[1:2,.(cols)] # NOT the desired result
##      cols
## 1:   Test
## 2: RESULT
labs[1:2,(cols)] # NOT the desired result
## [1] "Test"   "RESULT"

Subsetting by column index

labs[1:2,c(2,3,4,5)] # j can be any numeric vector but cannot be a vector name (use ..vectorname instead)
##    Test RESULT NORMAL.LOW NORMAL.HIGH
## 1: AGAP     -9          5          17
## 2: AGAP     -7          5          17
cols <- grep('norm',colnames(labs),ignore.case = TRUE)
labs[1:2,..cols]
##    NORMAL.LOW NORMAL.HIGH NORMAL.LOW.Flag NORMAL.HIGH.Flag
## 1:          5          17            <NA>             <NA>
## 2:          5          17            <NA>             <NA>
labs[1:2,-c(1,8)] # removes column 1 and 8
##    Test RESULT NORMAL.LOW NORMAL.HIGH CRITICAL.LOW CRITICAL.HIGH
## 1: AGAP     -9          5          17           NA            NA
## 2: AGAP     -7          5          17           NA            NA
##    NORMAL.LOW.Flag NORMAL.HIGH.Flag CRITICAL.LOW.Flag CRITICAL.HIGH.Flag
## 1:            <NA>             <NA>              <NA>               <NA>
## 2:            <NA>             <NA>              <NA>               <NA>
##    index
## 1:     1
## 2:     1

Using a function (slower than using colnames in j)

func <- function(dt,v) dt[,get(v)]
head(func(labs,'Test'))
## [1] "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP" "AGAP"

Using the .SD function together with the .SDcols argument

labs[2:3,.SD,.SDcols=2:3]
##    Test RESULT
## 1: AGAP     -7
## 2: AGAP     -4
labs[2:3,.SD,.SDcols=c('Test','RESULT')] # same as above
##    Test RESULT
## 1: AGAP     -7
## 2: AGAP     -4
labs[2:3,.SD,.SDcols=-c(1,8)] # same as labs[2:3,-c(1,8)]
##    Test RESULT NORMAL.LOW NORMAL.HIGH CRITICAL.LOW CRITICAL.HIGH
## 1: AGAP     -7          5          17           NA            NA
## 2: AGAP     -4          5          17           NA            NA
##    NORMAL.LOW.Flag NORMAL.HIGH.Flag CRITICAL.LOW.Flag CRITICAL.HIGH.Flag
## 1:            <NA>             <NA>              <NA>               <NA>
## 2:            <NA>             <NA>              <NA>               <NA>
##    index
## 1:     1
## 2:     1

Note: when the number of columns is huge (e.g. one for each gene), use the .SD function (without limiting the number of columns with .SDcols) carefully: it can hang for a long time. This is because .SD copies all columns except those specified in by to a separate data.table in memory before completing the operation.

Using like or grep for substring match

Not sure of the content of the Test column? For example, to get all the tests with ‘Hgb’ on the Test name:

labs[grep('Hgb',Test),table(Test)] # grep() produces an vector of row indices
## Test
##     Hgb Hgb A1c 
##   15098    1572
labs[grepl('Hgb',Test),table(Test)] # grepl() produces a logical vector 
## Test
##     Hgb Hgb A1c 
##   15098    1572
labs[grepl('Hgb',Test) | grepl('globin',Test),table(Test)] # grepl() better for combining with other logical vectors
## Test
## Hemoglobin BGA            Hgb        Hgb A1c 
##           1041          15098           1572
labs[grepl('Hgb|globin',Test),table(Test)] # same as above; grepl() can also use regular expressions
## Test
## Hemoglobin BGA            Hgb        Hgb A1c 
##           1041          15098           1572
labs[like(Test,'Hgb') | like(Test,'globin'),table(Test)] # same as above; like() is a shortcut for grepl()
## Test
## Hemoglobin BGA            Hgb        Hgb A1c 
##           1041          15098           1572
labs[Test %like% 'Hgb|globin',table(Test)] # same as above, similar to SQL
## Test
## Hemoglobin BGA            Hgb        Hgb A1c 
##           1041          15098           1572

Manipulations in j

Now we will get into some really time-saving features of data.table. Any R function from any package can be applied in j.

labs[Test=='Hct',mean(RESULT)] # reports the mean of all Hct results as a single element vector
## [1] 33.87336
labs[Test=='Hct',.(mean(RESULT),max(RESULT),min(RESULT),sd(RESULT))] # reports the function results as a data.table
##          V1   V2  V3       V4
## 1: 33.87336 72.7 3.7 6.874448
labs[Test=='Hct',.(Mean=mean(RESULT),Max=max(RESULT),Min=min(RESULT),CV=sd(RESULT)/mean(RESULT))]
##        Mean  Max Min        CV
## 1: 33.87336 72.7 3.7 0.2029456
labs[Test=='Hct',.(RESULT,Mean=mean(RESULT))] # Mean gets recycled on every column
##        RESULT     Mean
##     1:    3.7 33.87336
##     2:    7.1 33.87336
##     3:    7.5 33.87336
##     4:    7.5 33.87336
##     5:   11.2 33.87336
##    ---                
## 15100:   63.7 33.87336
## 15101:   65.0 33.87336
## 15102:   65.0 33.87336
## 15103:   68.5 33.87336
## 15104:   72.7 33.87336
labs[Test %in% c('Hct','Hgb'),{ # long pieces of code can be wrapped inside { }
  boxplot(RESULT~Test,outline=F)
  stripchart(RESULT~Test,method='jitter',vertical=TRUE,jitter=0.4,pch='.',col='gray',add=T)
  mtext("Hct & Hbg Test Boxplot",3)
}]

## NULL

Group by

This is one of the most powerful features of data.table, allowing aggregation of results depending on the content of one or more columns or even complex functions using column results. It uses the argument by= in the form [i, j, by].

DT::datatable(labs[,.(Average=mean(RESULT,na.rm=T),median=median(RESULT,na.rm=T),
        CV=sd(RESULT,na.rm=T)/mean(RESULT,na.rm=T)),by=Test])
DT::datatable(labs[,.(Average=mean(RESULT,na.rm=T),.N),
     by=Test][order(N,decreasing=T)]) # the function .N gives the number of rows per group and creates a column N by default in j
DT::datatable(labs[,.(Average=mean(RESULT,na.rm=T),.N),
     by=.(Test,NonNum)]) # gives all combinations of the two groups (check WBC: found clerical errors on CRITICAL.HIGH)
labs[Test=='WBC',.(Mean=mean(RESULT),.N),by=.(Test,NonNum,CRITICAL.HIGH)] # 
##    Test NonNum CRITICAL.HIGH      Mean     N
## 1:  WBC   TRUE          99.9  9.047113 14821
## 2:  WBC  FALSE          99.9 17.220221   272
labs[Test=='WBC',.(Mean=mean(RESULT),.N),
     by=.(Test,NumericThreshold=ifelse(NonNum,'Yes','No'))] # functions can be applied in by
##    Test NumericThreshold      Mean     N
## 1:  WBC              Yes  9.047113 14821
## 2:  WBC               No 17.220221   272
labs[,.N,by=.(encMRN,Test)] # number of repeated Tests per each MRN
##          encMRN              Test  N
##      1: 814dfd0              AGAP  5
##      2: 6ba834d              AGAP 15
##      3: 72e4e50              AGAP 16
##      4: 19f8d32              AGAP  3
##      5: dc35e6a              AGAP  6
##     ---                             
## 319080: 28e7ac5 pO2 Corrected Art  1
## 319081: d7a2f69 pO2 Corrected Art  1
## 319082: b0653a3 pO2 Corrected Art  1
## 319083: 51312e6 pO2 Corrected Art  1
## 319084: da2517b pO2 Corrected Art  1
DT::datatable(labs[,.N,by=.(encMRN,Test)][,.SD[which.max(N)],by=Test]) # maximum repeated tests per Test
labs[c('Hgb','Hct','Hgb A1c'),.N,by=.EACHI] # .EACHI is useful when **i** is a vector of multiple search values
##       Test     N
## 1:     Hgb 15098
## 2:     Hct 15104
## 3: Hgb A1c  1572

Additional data.table functions

shift

This function shifts an index (or any vector) by a set amount.

shortLabs <- labs
setkey(shortLabs,encMRN,Test)
shortlabs <- shortLabs[unique(encMRN)[1:3]][,1:5]
shortlabs[,Index:=1:.N,by=c('encMRN','Test')] # for each combination of encMRN and Test create an Index
DT::datatable(shortlabs[,Duplicate:=shift(Index,n = 1,type = 'lag'),by=c('encMRN','Test')]) # shifts index by one, so it corresponds to how many past Tests there are for each Test row in a given patient (assuming they are ordered by date)

frank

This function provides fast ranking of elements of a vector, list, data.frame or data.table.

head(frank(labs['Hct'],RESULT)) # rank of RESULT
## [1] 1
head(frank(labs['Hct'],RESULT,ties.method = 'dense')) # ties.method default is 'average'; others are "first", "random", "max", "min", and "dense"
## [1] 1
labs['Hct',.(Test,RESULT)][order(RESULT),.(RESULT,rank=frank(RESULT,ties.method = 'dense'))] 
##    RESULT rank
## 1:     NA    1

rleid

Run length-encoded (rle) vectors are a compressed way to encode repeated information. For example, the if the same RESULT 2 occurs 52 times in a row, an rle would have a value of 2 and a lenght of 52:

rleobj <- rle(labs['AGAP',RESULT])
head(cbind(value=rleobj$values,length=rleobj$lengths))
##      value length
## [1,]    NA      1

The function rleid provides a rle-like vector of the same length as the input, were the rleid changes when the values change:

head(labs['AGAP',.(RESULT,ID=rleid(RESULT))],10)
##    RESULT ID
## 1:     NA  1
labs['AGAP',.(Test,RESULT,ID=rleid(RESULT,prefix='group_'))][1:10]
##     Test RESULT      ID
##  1: <NA>     NA group_1
##  2: <NA>     NA    <NA>
##  3: <NA>     NA    <NA>
##  4: <NA>     NA    <NA>
##  5: <NA>     NA    <NA>
##  6: <NA>     NA    <NA>
##  7: <NA>     NA    <NA>
##  8: <NA>     NA    <NA>
##  9: <NA>     NA    <NA>
## 10: <NA>     NA    <NA>

uniqueN

labs['Hct',.N] # total number of rows for the 'Hct' Test
## [1] 1
labs['Hct',uniqueN(encMRN)] # total number of unique encMRN for the 'Hct' Test
## [1] 1
DT::datatable(labs[,.(UniqueMRN=uniqueN(encMRN),AvgTestPerPt=round(.N/uniqueN(encMRN),2)),by=Test])

Creating and Changing data.tables

Creating data.table from scratch

We can use the data.table() with each column as a vector, just like for data.frames. We can set the key at creation time with the key= argument

samp <- sample(1:nrow(labs),10) # random sample of labs' rows
(shortlabs <- data.table(MRN=labs$encMRN[samp],Result=labs$RESULT[samp],Test=labs$Test[samp],OriginalOrder=c(1:10),Even=c(0,1),key='Test')) # Note that the vector for the Even column has lenght 2, therefore it is recycled (before sorting by Test)
##         MRN Result          Test OriginalOrder Even
##  1: 5229eb8 15.000          AGAP             5    0
##  2: dd0c377 45.000           BUN            10    1
##  3: 6a0916a  1.000 Basophil Auto             1    0
##  4: a1498fa  0.890    Creatinine             4    1
##  5: 9ee78d1 60.006 GFR Afro-Amer             8    1
##  6: e0d8ec4 52.000 GFR Afro-Amer             9    0
##  7: e930e4e 28.700           MCH             3    0
##  8: 5c530b1  0.000     NRBC Auto             6    1
##  9: 88e2e50  3.370           RBC             2    1
## 10: d00e395  1.530      iCA-EPOC             7    0

Creating data.table from another object

You can convert data.frames or matrices to data.tables and vice versa

shortlabs <- as.data.frame(shortlabs);class(shortlabs)
## [1] "data.frame"
shortlabs <- as.data.table(shortlabs);class(shortlabs)
## [1] "data.table" "data.frame"

Using set family of functions

change sorting order, column names, column order

setorder(labs,Test,encMRN,RESULT) # sorts by the columns mentioned as arguments and if it results in reordering of the keys, sets the key to NULL, so labs['Hct' no longer works]
(cols <- colnames(labs)) # note that with set functions, all previously assigned variables derived from the data.table are dynamically changed: check cols after setcolorder or setnames; this is NOT normal behavior in R, only happens with data.table set functions

setkey(labs,Test,RESULT);key(labs) # as above but sets the keys

Transposing and splitting

Transpose

cols <- colnames(shortlabs)
shortlabst <- transpose(shortlabs[1:5]) # same as t() for data.frames;
setnames(shortlabst,shortlabs$MRN[1:5])[,cols:=cols] # colnames and rownames are lost but can be added afterward
shortlabst <- shortlabst[2:nrow(shortlabst)] # deleted the first row, which was promoted to colnames
shortlabst
##          6a0916a 88e2e50 e930e4e    a1498fa 5229eb8          cols
## 1:             1    3.37    28.7       0.89      15        Result
## 2: Basophil Auto     RBC     MCH Creatinine    AGAP          Test
## 3:             1       2       3          4       5 OriginalOrder
## 4:             0       1       0          1       0          Even
## 5:             1       0       1          0       1           Odd
## 6:             1       2       3          4    <NA>     FirstFour
## 7:          <NA>    <NA>    <NA>       <NA>    <NA>      LastFour

Transpose and split

This is very useful for fields that contain “sub-fields” separated by a character.

shortlabs[1:4,complexField:=c('John|Smith|New York','Jane|Doe','|Doe|London','||Paris')]
shortlabs[,c('FirstName','LastName','City'):=tstrsplit(complexField,split='\\|')][] # Splits the complexField into 3 columns; the \\ is necessary for | to be interpreted as a character and not as the OR operator; alternatively use fixed=TRUE argument
